##Ambulance drivers in Wuhan: A race against death

"All we want now is for patients to be treated. Beds are really tight and the lack of beds is a daily problem for our staff at the first aid station, " said a station chief, "We're not afraid of the traffic, we're afraid of the patients coming to the hospital without beds. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Emergency workers at work. Photo provided by interviewee

Wang Shuangxing, editor, Hsinking Daily News

On Feb. 3,10 ambulances equipped with portable suction machines, oxygen cylinders and other medical equipment arrived at Huoshenshan hospital with the first batch of seriously ill patients.

Lu Yao, a 32-year-old driver of one of the ambulances, took a photo with his colleagues outside the hospital as night fell. In the photo, his left hand is clenched in front of his chest. The ambulance is parked behind him, its blue warning light flashing.

For the past few decades, these ambulance lights have been flashing on the streets of Wuhan night and day, connecting patients to hospitals.

Xiangyang, 56, is also an ambulance driver. In the year of destiny, there's still work to be done. He said, see all life and death, sometimes also can not help, can only one trip out of the car, run on the road, to do their work well.

He replaced the background of his social media profile with a photo of himself in front of an ambulance, with a profile page that read, I've been racing death my whole life.

━━━━━

Keep your foot on the gas for 24 hours

At 0.37 am on January 31, the bell rang in the duty room and Xiangyang received a call from the emergency center dispatcher to pick up a suspected case of new pneumonia in the Kong Hon district.

Quickly notify the medical staff, put on protective clothing, isolation clothing, wear masks, goggles, etc. , they set off in 4 minutes.

A doctor, a nurse, a driver, and two stretcher bearers form a first aid unit that is standard on every ambulance. In order to save time, and the Rescue Party to verify the address, inquire about the condition of the work, all on the road.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taking care of patients in an ambulance while transferring patients. Photo courtesy of the respondents

The patient's daughter answered the phone, crying, "you must come. ". Her 64-year-old mother was in a coma.

The house was in an old residential area, sealed off from the road, turned in circles toward the sun before driving nearby, and the stretcher bearers took a side road, crossed a narrow staircase and carried the patient to an ambulance.

The patient's daughter, who could not stop coughing, said she had been running a fever for days. The doctor judges, she may also be infected, suggested to go to the hospital with a test. Five, six-year-olds left alone.

Many families have more than one suspected case, either two or more, Xiangyang said.

One of Xiangyang's fellow drivers recalled to the press that he and his team had been called to Hankou on January 28. A three-person family was called for help. The driver asked, which one is the patient? The response: All three.

Close the door and turn to the sun and drive the ambulance to the nearest hospital. Medical staff in the cab behind the car, to patients do ECG monitoring, blood oxygen, on the suction machine.

A short tap on the glass rang out, turning toward the sun, and the doctor made a sign to him: six, zero. This means his oxygen level is down to 60(normal oxygen level is about 90% , and his oxygen level is dangerously low) , and the doctor tells him to drive faster. It's urgent.

Sunward pressed down on the gas.

On that day, as on many previous days, nearly 20 patients were transported to Xiangyang. Emergency Centre staff are rotated in three shifts, working 24 hours a day and resting for two days. Before the outbreak, a shift (24 hours) usually transports seven or eight patients.

In the past, the entire Wuhan Emergency Center received about 3,000 calls a day for help. Today, the number is more than 10,000, up to 15,000, Zhu Kang, an emergency worker in Wuhan, told reporters. When there are many patients, people who call 120 a day have to wait in line for at least 600.

More than one patient said after seeing Xiangyang: "there are hundreds of people waiting in line, and finally it's me. "

So, and Xiangyang the same emergency workers, do not sleep to run on the road. They are distributed in 57 first aid stations all over the city. After receiving the dispatch order from the first aid center, they drive 87 ambulances and 10 negative-pressure ambulances to deliver batches of patients to the hospital.

Lu Yao, the driver, was driving one of the 10 first-aid vehicles in Wuhan, which can minimize the risk of cross-infection among medical personnel and discharge the air inside the vehicle after harmless treatment, mostly used to transport confirmed cases.

From January 17, Lu Yao participated in the first batch of confirmed patients transfer work, transfer of patients from various hospitals to designated hospitals. On 3 February, he was also involved in the transfer of patients to the Vulcan Mountain Hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 3, Lu Yao and colleagues in the Fire Mountain Hospital photo. Photo courtesy of the respondents

"We're not afraid of the traffic. We're afraid of the beds. "

In the early morning of January 31, Xiangyang was carrying his sick mother and daughter to the hospital. A blue warning light flashes in the darkness of Wuhan, and sirens are rarely heard because there are few cars on the road.

On January 23, Wuhan announced that it would "close the corridor away from the Han River, " immediately following the ban on motor vehicles in the central city. The city became quiet, and the sun began to drive ambulances down the road. There were no more traffic jams, and few other vehicles, even the occasional ones, could be seen, in addition to transport vehicles, transport to and from the medical staff to work, official vehicles, the rest is the same as his ambulance. On weekdays, the streets occasionally pass three or two figures, the basic people out to buy food, hat mask, tight.

After the patient was sent to the nearest hospital, the family was told that there were no beds in the hospital for a long time.

The doctor in the ambulance went to talk to the doctor in the hospital, and even started arguing. "We were all medical staff, " he recalled. "We understood the rules and reasoning, but we were all worried when we saw the patient unconscious. "

Finally, after negotiation, the hospital agreed to register the unconscious old man first. Xiangyang ran to find three benches, side by side, and then together with the stretcher bearers to carry the old man to the bench, waiting for hospital treatment.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xiangyang and his colleagues didn't have much time to stay. They had another job to do, and they had to drive back to the first aid station as quickly as possible to disinfect the car and then rush to transfer the next patient.

When leaving, the sun looked back, the old man fell asleep on the bench, the daughter leaned on the side, with his hands around his mother's head.

"that girl is not much older than my girl, " Xiangyang said, tears streaming down his eyes. The doctor in one side is quite surprised: "You have seen so many, still like this. "

Since the outbreak, Xiangyang says, he has been worried every time he goes out of the car, worried about sending patients to the hospital and not being admitted or registered.

Almost every emergency center worker has been caught up in this sense of powerlessness. Sometimes, drivers say, they even have to drag patients "several times" , one hospital can not be admitted, rushed to the next hospital, whether bed, observation beds, or fever clinic, are full. Most of the time, patients were carried by the sun to three hospitals in a row, the final coordination of the hospital by the doctor. Lu Yao once drove patients to four hospitals, until the fourth was registered.

Sometimes, she recalled, ambulances pulled patients and even sent them to several hospitals without being able to receive treatment, so anxious that the staff on the buses went around asking for help, "Call the emergency center first, and if you can't, call me, and I'll ask the head of our department to see if I can go to the fever clinic first. " (most emergency stations are attached to the Emergency Department of a hospital, which manages them together with the emergency center.)

Use Protective materials sparingly

According to current information, COVID-19 pneumonia is definitely a human to human transmission, Zhong Nanshan, a member of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and head of the High Level Expert Group of the National Health Commission, told CCTV on the evening of January 20. The next day, first responders, like Xiangyang, went to Defcon 3.

By late January, Xiangyang and his colleagues were getting busier and busier, often just finishing a patient, not yet back to the first aid station, received the next task, after disinfection, immediately set out.

Disinfection is an important step in the prevention and treatment of new coronary pneumonia. Once a patient has been transported, every corner of the ambulance needs to be disinfected. We'll start with 75 proof alcohol, then we'll use disinfectant, and then we'll turn on the UV light, and we'll sterilize for half an hour.

Strictly speaking, masks, protective clothing is also a one-time, to complete a transfer, should be replaced with a protective equipment. But special period, can only"economize".

Protective clothing glue is a one-time, want to wear repeatedly, can only carefully tear a small incision, carefully take off, with alcohol and disinfection water treatment again, and then hanging to ultraviolet light disinfection, the next car to continue to wear.

Sunward suits tend to wear "two or two and a half shifts, " or 48 to 60 hours. The isolation clothing is relatively sufficient, everybody then puts it to wear outside the protective clothing, every go to work, may change a new isolation clothing.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The first-aid workers put on a layer of protective clothing before leaving the car. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Xiangyang is the oldest one in the station. "everyone takes good care of me. I basically change an N95 mask every two days. None of the younger ones seem to change so quickly. Sometimes a mask needs to be worn for three to four days. " In order to protect myself, two more surgical masks per shift.

Xiangyang had seen the head nurse go to the Dean for supplies, "get into a fight, come back crying. " . After all understand: The hospital also has fever clinic, infection department, Isolation Ward, we are all in the first line.

"At present, the protective materials of the entire emergency center are still insufficient, " said Zhu Kang, a worker at the Wuhan Emergency Center. "although some materials are being delivered, the gap is still very large. "

Zhu Kang said that unlike hospitals, emergency centers have a higher demand for protective materials. Ideally, emergency workers should change their protective clothing every time a patient is transported to prevent cross-infection.

He calculates conservatively that there are 57 stations throughout the centre, each receiving more than 10 patients a day, some more than 20. At 12 visits, there must be 680 visits per day; at the current rate of 75 per cent of patients with fever, 480 sets of protective clothing are also required; and 50 sets of protective clothing per case, at least 10 boxes per day.

But in fact, the emergency center's protective materials are not rationed. "when they raise money from the top, they send it. If they don't, they find their own way, " Zhu said. "They can only ask the stationmasters to find their own way. If they have the ability, they raise more, and if they don't, they raise less. "

A station master said that at the beginning of the epidemic prevention and control, almost all the station's protective supplies were very scarce. Everyone thought of various ways and went to the hospital warehouse every day to look for protective supplies that could be used, also immediately non-stop to rush over, for fear to get late.

Today, protective materials from all over the country are being sent to Wuhan one after another. Some first aid stations have adequate goggles and protective clothing, but lack N95 masks. Some stations are still in short supply and need help everywhere, an average of three or four times per transfer, you can change into a suit.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xiangyang received some protective gear from someone on the Internet

"then there's the country and the family. What if you quit them? "

When the outbreak, Xiangyang could not have returned to Wuhan.

On January 22, twenty-eight, he sent his daughter to Beijing to study. At night, Wuhan Pneumonia Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters issued notice No. 1, said: from January 23,2020 at 10:00, the city bus, subway, ferry, long-distance passenger transport suspended operations; the airport, Railway Station from the Han passage temporarily closed. Immediately afterward, Wuhan "closes the city" The news to be all over the Internet.

Flights back to Wuhan were canceled, and Xiangyang contacted the authorities and the Beijing Railway Bureau, eventually boarding a high speed train from Beijing to Zhuhai, he and the conductor said: "I am a medical staff, have to go back. " Next to the passenger answered: "Do not get off, it is like this, you still rush back? " Xiangyang insisted, finally through Wuhan, a person got off the car.

"I come from a military background. That's what I was taught. You can't retreat. Behind you is your country and your family. What if you retreat them? "

He and his colleagues did not retreat, until today, still driving the white ambulance, through the streets of Wuhan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The staff at the first aid station ate in the on-call room. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Now, Xiangyang's emergency station, more than 40 staff, four people have new symptoms of pneumonia, isolation treatment in the hospital, waiting to be diagnosed. They live in the isolation ward on the floor, treatment of the majority of the hospital was infected with the medical staff.

Emergency Center Staff Zhu Kang, now, in addition to a few emergency stations, other stations, "have people were involved. ". One of the station because of the driver infection, the stationmaster had to find a temporary driver, "ran a car, feeling too scary, quit. "

Recently, a stretcher-bearer who was standing next to Xiangyang also "quit. " . Stretcher bearers mostly from the surrounding counties and townships in Wuhan, after closing the Han Channel, many field stretcher bearers can not come back, once the vacancy is difficult to fill. There is only one stretcher-bearer left in the group, and it can only be a driver or a doctor. "We can't afford to lose any of them now, " Xiangyang said.

Beginning in mid-january, emergency staff at various stations were consolidated in their units because of the increased workload and fears of possible transmission of the virus to their families. Each duty room has two beds up and down, not enough to free up storage room for people, not enough, stay in the hospital staff arranged for the hotel.

After traffic control, demand for 120 ambulances rose, and Xiangyang and his colleagues became busier. On more than one occasion, however, 120 was called to report that the patient was unconscious, delirious, and convulsing. When the ambulance arrived, the patient walked down the stairs.

During working hours, emergency center staff are on the line 24 hours a day; rest time is also used for disinfection and material handling. An emergency doctor wrote in his work notes: Now, our workload is getting bigger and bigger. Originally, a class had 7-8 trips, now it is normal for a class to have 14-15 trips, basically every trip, the next bus will be out soon after disinfection, the night to sleep a couple of hours is a complete hope.

Some first aid workers have an average age of more than 50, and the youngest nurse, born in 1976, is still on the job, day and night. Vulcan Mountain Hospital has begun to receive treatment, Raytheon Mountain Hospital immediately completed, front-line staff often said: "It is going to be better. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Starting a week ago, a local fast-food restaurant gave free lunch to more than 20 staff members on duty every day. Photo courtesy of the respondents

The driver, Lu Yao's lover, was home alone with two small children. When he was off duty, he would video chat with his family over dinner. His 6 year old daughter, who had no idea about viruses, held her phone and told her father that she had played the piano and practiced dancing after finishing her homework today. Every time before the end of the call, the lover will always take over the phone, repeatedly nagging "must do a good job of protection. ". Half a month ago, she wanted to persuade Lu Yao do not go to work, Lu Yao responded: "This time, how possible. "

It's common to skip meals at work, Xiangyang says. Lunch at 45 p.m. , dinner until 11 or 12 p.m. is common. I couldn't find a restaurant that was open, so I bought instant noodles. Sometimes I'm so busy going out that I can't even eat all day.

A week ago, a local fast-food restaurant every day to the duty of more than 20 staff to send free lunch, a meat one vegetarian two dishes, plus a bowl of soup. There is a post-it note on the package of each meal, "everything will be all right. " "please protect yourself. You take care of the patient, we take care of you, don't forget there are people waiting for you to come home for dinner, please come back safely, one of the nurses in the group cried on the spot.

Xiangyang tore them off one by one, neatly, pasted on the desk in the duty room.

(Xiangyang, Luyao, Zhu Kang and Hayashida were given pseudonyms.)
